Title: Frankenstein
Credit: Written by
Author: Mary Wollstonecraft (Godwin) Shelley
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 3/6/2026
Notes: Period gothic live-action; cold palette; candlelight and ice; one continuous render medium for all figures

===

EXT. ST. PETERSBURGH - STREET - DAY

Northern wind. Sledges hiss over packed snow. 

ROBERT WALTON, late twenties, lean, weather-roughened, dark hair under a fur cap, wrapped in heavy furs, walks with bright, restless eyes. Period late-eighteenth-century dress beneath the furs. He turns his face into the cold as if drinking it.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
St. Petersburgh, December eleventh, seventeen—.

INT. WALTON'S LODGINGS - NIGHT

A small room, lamp-lit. Walton writes at a wooden table. Ink, paper, a worn volume of voyage accounts.

WALTON (V.O.)
To Mrs. Saville, England. You will rejoice to hear that no disaster has accompanied the commencement of an enterprise which you have regarded with such evil forebodings.

He pauses, touches the page, continues.

WALTON (V.O.)
I am already far north of London. This breeze, which has travelled from the regions towards which I am advancing, gives me a foretaste of those icy climes. I try in vain to be persuaded that the pole is the seat of frost and desolation. What may not be expected in a country of eternal light?

He looks toward the dark window — frost on the glass.

WALTON (V.O.)
I shall satiate my ardent curiosity with the sight of a part of the world never before visited. These are my enticements, and they are sufficient to conquer all fear of danger or death.

EXT. FROZEN ROAD NORTH - DAY

A sledge races through white waste. Walton, fur-wrapped, eyes fixed ahead.

WALTON (V.O.)
I preferred glory to every enticement that wealth placed in my path. Oh, that some encouraging voice would answer in the affirmative. My courage and my resolution is firm; but my hopes fluctuate, and my spirits are often depressed.

EXT. ARCHANGEL HARBOR - DAY

Masts, ice fringe, working men. Walton inspects a sturdy vessel with THE MASTER, forties, mild-faced, steady, and THE LIEUTENANT, thirties, English, hard-eyed, hungry for advancement. Sailors load casks.

WALTON (V.O.)
Archangel, March twenty-eighth. I have hired a vessel and am occupied in collecting my sailors; those whom I have already engaged appear to be men on whom I can depend.

INT. SHIP - CAPTAIN'S CABIN - NIGHT

Walton alone at a narrow desk. The ship creaks. He writes more slowly.

WALTON (V.O.)
But I have one want which I have never yet been able to satisfy. I have no friend, Margaret. When I am glowing with the enthusiasm of success, there will be none to participate my joy; if I am assailed by disappointment, no one will endeavour to sustain me in dejection. I desire the company of a man who could sympathise with me, whose eyes would reply to mine.

He sets the pen down. Listens to the empty timber.

EXT. ARCTIC SEA - DAY

Endless ice and open leads. Walton's ship locked in white. Crew on deck, breath smoking. Walton at the rail with a glass, scanning the waste. The Lieutenant beside him.

LIEUTENANT
The pack closes tighter each watch, sir.

WALTON
We hold. Glory does not keep to fair latitudes.

A distant dark shape on the ice — too far, then gone in glare.

EXT. ARCTIC ICE - DAY

Days later. Fog and broken floes. Sailors shout. Walton climbs the rail.

Through the glass: a sledge, dogs nearly spent — and a HUMAN FIGURE, collapsed, frost in his dark hair.

WALTON
There! A man — on the floe!

EXT. ICE FLOE BESIDE THE SHIP - DAY

Sailors haul aboard VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN: thirties, once-handsome, now gaunt to the bone, hollow cheeks, fever-bright eyes, cracked lips, ruined gentleman's clothes under borrowed furs. He clings to life by will alone.

Walton kneels, wraps him.

WALTON
You are safe. Rest. What madness drove you onto the ice alone?

Victor's eyes open — not relief, pursuit.

VICTOR
He... must not escape. North. Always north.

He collapses into Walton's arms.

INT. SHIP - SICK BAY CABIN - NIGHT

Oil lamp. Victor on a berth, wrapped in blankets. Color faintly returning. Walton sits beside him with broth.

Victor studies Walton's face with sudden, painful interest.

VICTOR
You seek a passage where none has been. You would be the first to tread a land never imprinted by the foot of man.

WALTON
How do you know me?

VICTOR
I know the look. I had it once. Ambition without a friend to check it.

He coughs; Walton steadies the cup.

WALTON
I have wanted such a friend my whole voyage.

VICTOR
Then hear me. And if you are a man of science and of feeling, learn what I have paid for knowledge.

Victor stares at the lamp flame.

VICTOR
I am by birth a Genevese. I created a being... and fled from what I made.

MATCH CUT TO:

INT. VICTOR'S LABORATORY - NIGHT (FLASHBACK)

Sparse, filmable gothic chamber: instruments, glass, a large form under sheet on a table. Victor younger, exhausted, stained coat, hair wild — same man, not yet ruined.

A hand — yellowed, oversized, suture-marked — twitches from beneath the sheet.

Victor pulls the cloth.

THE CREATURE lies there: eight feet of assembled flesh, black lips, watery yellow eye opening, lustrous black hair, skin scarcely hiding muscles and arteries; terrible proportion, not cartoon — the same live-action medium as all others.

The yellow eye fixes on Victor.

Victor staggers back in horror.

VICTOR
No—

He turns, flees into darkness.

The Creature sits up slowly, alone, bewildered, breathing.

EXT. GERMAN FOREST AND FIELDS - DAWN TO NIGHT (MONTAGE)

The Creature wanders: huge frame in scavenged rough clothes, moving with surprising agility. Villagers glimpse him — scream, hurl stones. He flees, wounded, into woods.

He learns fire, hunger, cold. Drinks from streams. Hides from daylight.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He was endued with a figure hideously deformed and loathsome; his stature far exceeded theirs. When he looked around he saw and heard of none like him.

EXT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - EDGE OF WOOD - DAY

A poor, neat cottage with a small garden and adjoining shed. Smoke from the chimney.

The Creature watches from a chink in the woodpile / lean-to wall — a hidden hovel against the cottage side, straw, darkness. His eye at a crack.

INT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - DAY

Through the Creature's viewpoint crack:

DE LACEY, elderly, blind, silver hair, gentle face, sits with a stick. AGATHA, young, worn-kind, plain dress, sweeps and cooks. FELIX, young, strong, handsome, works with quiet bitterness, carries wood, tends the garden.

They move with poverty and tenderness. Agatha kisses her father's hand. Felix reads aloud; the old man smiles toward the sound.

INT. CREATURE'S HOVEL - NIGHT

The Creature curls in straw, listening to soft voices through the wall. He places scavenged root vegetables and firewood silently at the cottage door — unseen charity.

EXT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - DAWN

Felix finds the wood and food. Wonder. Agatha looks to the trees. De Lacey turns his blind face toward the morning air.

DE LACEY
Some good neighbor watches us.

INT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - DAY

Seasons turn in light through the window. The family at table, sparse meals. Felix teaches; Agatha sings a simple air.

The Creature, at his crack, mouthing words silently, learning.

CREATURE (V.O.)
My days were spent in close attention, that I might more speedily master the language.

EXT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - DAY

A stranger arrives on the path: SAFIE, young, dark-haired, luminous, travel-worn Eastern dress, guitar among her bundles. Felix runs to her — joy breaks his gloom. He embraces her. Agatha kisses Safie's hands. De Lacey rises, radiant without sight.

FELIX
Safe. You are safe.

He leads her in. The Creature watches, astonished by their happiness.

INT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - EVENING

Safie at De Lacey's feet with the guitar. She plays; a rich, aching melody. Tears on the old man's cheeks. Agatha takes the guitar after, simpler air. Felix cannot stop smiling.

FELIX
Good night, sweet Safie.

Safie and Agatha retire. Felix sits long with his father, repeating her name in soft talk.

INT. CREATURE'S HOVEL - NIGHT

The Creature whispers the new name, practicing.

CREATURE
(soft)
Safie... Safie.

INT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - DAY

Days later. Felix instructs Safie from a book — Volney's Ruins of Empires — pointing, explaining slowly. Safie repeats words. Agatha sews. De Lacey listens.

The Creature drinks every syllable through the wall.

FELIX
Nations rise... and fall. Men make laws... and break them.

SAFIE
(broken accent, earnest)
Laws... men...

CREATURE (V.O.)
Through this work I obtained a cursory knowledge of history. I heard of the slothful Asiatics, of the stupendous genius of the Grecians, of the wars of the early Romans, of chivalry, Christianity, and kings. I heard of the discovery of the American hemisphere and wept with Safie over the hapless fate of its original inhabitants.

INT. CREATURE'S HOVEL - NIGHT

The Creature's face at the crack — wonder turning to anguish.

CREATURE (V.O.)
Was man, indeed, at once so powerful, so virtuous and magnificent, yet so vicious and base? To be a great and virtuous man appeared the highest honour; to be base and vicious, the lowest degradation.

EXT. WOODS NEAR COTTAGE - NIGHT

Moonlight. The Creature walks among flowers and pale trees, huge and careful, never by day.

CREATURE (V.O.)
I learned of the division of property, of immense wealth and squalid poverty, of rank and noble blood. The possessions most esteemed were high descent united with riches. And what was I? Of my creation and creator I was absolutely ignorant. I possessed no money, no friends, no kind of property. Was I, then, a monster, a blot upon the earth, from which all men fled and whom all men disowned?

He sinks to his knees among the roots.

CREATURE (V.O.)
Oh, that I had for ever remained in my native wood, nor known nor felt beyond the sensations of hunger, thirst, and heat!

INT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - DAY

Spring light. Safie and Felix at lessons; laughter. Agatha braids flowers. De Lacey turns toward the warmth of the room.

The Creature watches — love and exile together.

CREATURE (V.O.)
I admired virtue and good feelings and loved the gentle manners of my cottagers, but I was shut out from intercourse with them. The gentle words of Agatha and the animated smiles of the charming Arabian were not for me.

INT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - DAY

The room empty of the young people — only De Lacey by the hearth. The door creaks.

The Creature enters, ducking, trembling, trying to soften his vast frame. Soft daylight on his terrible face and kind, terrified eyes.

CREATURE
Pardon this intrusion. I am a traveller, in want of rest. You are blind; I will not offend your eyes. Only... hear me. I am alone. I seek friends.

De Lacey turns, gentle, unafraid of what he cannot see.

DE LACEY
Do not fear. A true friend is a rare gift. Sit. Speak. If you are in trouble, I will try to help you.

The Creature almost sobs — a huge hand near the old man's.

CREATURE
I have watched this house. I have loved its people. If I can but win them—

Footsteps. Felix, Agatha, and Safie enter with baskets.

They see the Creature.

Agatha screams. Safie faints against the wall. Felix roars, seizes a stick—

FELIX
Demon—!

He beats the Creature, drives him. The Creature does not strike back — shields his head, crashes out through the door, wailing.

EXT. DE LACEY COTTAGE - CONTINUOUS

The Creature flees into the trees as Felix stands in the doorway, chest heaving, protecting his family. De Lacey calls blindly from within.

DE LACEY
Felix? What has happened? Who was there?

EXT. DEEP FOREST - NIGHT

Rain. The Creature howls, tears at his hair, then falls silent — something colder settling in him.

CREATURE
I am alone... and they are virtuous. Then virtue is not for me.

Lightning far off. His yellow eyes open with a new resolve.

INT. SHIP - SICK BAY CABIN - NIGHT (PRESENT)

Back with Walton and Victor. Victor's voice is nearly gone; sweat on his brow.

VICTOR
He murdered those I loved. William. Clerval. Elizabeth on our bridal night. He led me into this ice to make of my life one long pursuit. I raised him... and would not own him. My work is finished. Yours... must not become mine.

Walton grips Victor's hand.

WALTON
Rest. I will not abandon you.

Victor's eyes fix on nothing. A long breath leaves him. Stillness.

Walton bows his head.

WALTON
Frankenstein—

The cabin lamp gutters. A shadow fills the doorway from the deck.

THE CREATURE stands there, frost on his black hair, the same enormous stitched frame, eyes on the corpse. Grief contorts the inhuman face.

Walton starts up, horror and fury.

The Creature moves to the berth, ignores Walton at first, looks down at Victor.

CREATURE
Oh, Frankenstein... generous and self-devoted being! What does it avail that I now ask thee to pardon me? I, who irretrievably destroyed thee by destroying all thou lovedst.

Walton finds his voice.

WALTON
Your repentance is now superfluous. If you had listened to the voice of conscience before you had urged your diabolical vengeance to this extremity, Frankenstein would yet have lived.

The Creature turns — eloquence and agony.

CREATURE
And do you dream? Do you think that I was then dead to agony and remorse? He — 

(pointing to the corpse)

— he suffered not in the consummation of the deed. Not the ten-thousandth portion of the anguish that was mine during the lingering detail of its execution. My heart was fashioned to be susceptible of love and sympathy, and when wrenched by misery to vice and hatred, it did not endure the violence of the change without torture such as you cannot even imagine.

WALTON
Wretch! It is well that you come here to whine over the desolation that you have made. You throw a torch into a pile of buildings, and when they are consumed, you sit among the ruins and lament the fall. Hypocritical fiend!

CREATURE
Oh, it is not thus — not thus. Yet such must be the impression conveyed by what appears to be the purport of my actions. I seek not a fellow feeling in my misery. No sympathy may I ever find. Once my fancy was soothed with dreams of virtue, of fame, and of enjoyment. Once I falsely hoped to meet with beings who, pardoning my outward form, would love me for the excellent qualities which I was capable of unfolding. But now crime has degraded me beneath the meanest animal. The fallen angel becomes a malignant devil. Yet even that enemy of God and man had friends and associates in his desolation; I am alone.

He looks again at Victor.

CREATURE
You, who call Frankenstein your friend, seem to have a knowledge of my crimes and his misfortunes. But he could not sum up the hours and months of misery which I endured. While I destroyed his hopes, I did not satisfy my own desires. Still I desired love and fellowship, and I was still spurned. Was there no injustice in this? Am I to be thought the only criminal, when all humankind sinned against me? Why do you not hate Felix, who drove me from his door with contumely? I, the miserable and the abandoned, am an abortion, to be spurned at, and kicked, and trampled on.

Walton's anger falters — not forgiveness, but stricken attention.

CREATURE
But it is true that I am a wretch. I have murdered the lovely and the helpless; I have strangled the innocent as they slept. I have devoted my creator to misery; I have pursued him even to that irremediable ruin. There he lies, white and cold in death. You hate me, but your abhorrence cannot equal that with which I regard myself.

He lifts his own hands, stares at them.

CREATURE
I look on the hands which executed the deed; I think on the heart in which the imagination of it was conceived and long for the moment when these hands will meet my eyes, when that imagination will haunt my thoughts no more.

EXT. SHIP DECK - ARCTIC NIGHT - CONTINUOUS

Walton follows as the Creature moves toward the rail. Ice raft and black water beyond. Wind. The Lieutenant and Master watch from a distance, frozen by the figure's size.

CREATURE
Fear not that I shall be the instrument of future mischief. My work is nearly complete. Neither yours nor any man's death is needed to consummate the series of my being, but it requires my own. I shall quit your vessel on the ice raft which brought me thither and shall seek the most northern extremity of the globe. I shall collect my funeral pile and consume to ashes this miserable frame, that its remains may afford no light to any curious and unhallowed wretch who would create such another as I have been. I shall die. I shall no longer feel the agonies which now consume me.

He faces Walton fully — final.

CREATURE
Farewell. I leave you, and in you the last of humankind whom these eyes will ever behold. Farewell, Frankenstein! Blasted as thou wert, my agony was still superior to thine, for the bitter sting of remorse will not cease to rankle in my wounds until death shall close them for ever.

(voice rising, solemn)

But soon I shall die, and what I now feel be no longer felt. Soon these burning miseries will be extinct. I shall ascend my funeral pile triumphantly and exult in the agony of the torturing flames. The light of that conflagration will fade away; my ashes will be swept into the sea by the winds. My spirit will sleep in peace, or if it thinks, it will not surely think thus. Farewell.

He springs from the cabin-rail / stern onto the ice raft alongside.

EXT. ARCTIC SEA - NIGHT

The raft drives off among the floes. The Creature's dark shape stands upright a moment against the pale ice and night — then is borne away by the waves and lost in darkness and distance.

Walton at the rail, alone, the wind on his face as in Petersburg — but the delight is gone. Behind him, through the open way, Victor's body lies still.

WALTON (V.O.)
You will have heard, Margaret, of the strange events of this voyage. I have lost the friend my heart required... and seen what a man may make, when he would play at being God.

The ship creaks in the pack. White waste to the horizon.

FADE OUT.

THE END
